    {
      "fullUrl": "urn:uuid:eae25758-21bb-4bac-a4f2-3a00163b0b0f",
      "resource": {
        "resourceType": "Communication",
        "status": "completed",
        "text": {
          "status": "generated",
          "div": "<div xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml\">patient-description</div>"
        },
        "category": [
          {
            "coding": [
              {
                "system": "urn:virpat:fhir:doc-type",
                "code": "patient-description"
              }
            ]
          }
        ],
        "subject": {
          "reference": "urn:uuid:11111111-1111-4111-8111-111111111111"
        },
        "payload": [
          {
            "contentString": "{patientName} is a 38-year-old woman who appears mildly fatigued but remains fully ambulatory and engaged during conversation. She has a slightly sallow complexion and occasionally rubs the right upper part of her abdomen when seated for long periods, describing a dull discomfort beneath the ribs. Over the past several weeks she has noticed reduced energy, intermittent nausea, poor appetite, and a sense of abdominal fullness after meals. On some days she reports darkened urine and mild generalized itching, though she has not had severe pain or overt confusion. Her build is average, and she dresses neatly in business-casual clothing, presenting as organized and health-conscious but clearly worried by persistent symptoms she cannot explain.\n\nShe works as a project coordinator for a regional marketing firm, a job that is mostly desk-based and involves periodic deadline-related stress. Her daily routine is busy, often leading to skipped lunches and irregular hydration. She lives with her partner and school-aged daughter, and her evenings are usually spent helping with homework, preparing meals, or catching up on administrative work from home. She does not smoke and drinks alcohol only socially, typically one to two glasses of wine on weekends, though she has recently stopped drinking entirely because it seemed to worsen her nausea.\n\nIn terms of lifestyle, {patientName} tries to stay active with weekend walks, beginner yoga classes, and gardening on her apartment balcony. She enjoys cooking, especially Mediterranean-style meals, although lately she has preferred bland foods because richer meals make her feel unwell. She has a supportive circle of friends and close contact with her sister and mother, both of whom have encouraged her to seek medical care after noticing she looks more tired than usual. She is generally independent and accustomed to functioning at a high level, which makes her recent decline in stamina particularly frustrating.\n\nSocially and emotionally, {patientName} is thoughtful and somewhat anxious about her health, mainly because the symptoms have persisted longer than expected. She denies illicit drug use and has no high-risk occupational exposures, but she does mention taking several over-the-counter herbal wellness supplements intermittently over the past few months. She is attentive to medical advice and motivated to make changes if needed. Her overall presentation is that of an otherwise active adult woman with subacute constitutional and hepatobiliary symptoms concerning for inflammatory liver involvement."
          }
        ]
      }
    },
    {
      "fullUrl": "urn:uuid:946bca71-b5d8-462d-ba57-dbdcc8bc6a97",
      "resource": {
        "resourceType": "Communication",
        "status": "completed",
        "text": {
          "status": "generated",
          "div": "<div xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml\">patient-history</div>"
        },
        "category": [
          {
            "coding": [
              {
                "system": "urn:virpat:fhir:doc-type",
                "code": "patient-history"
              }
            ]
          }
        ],
        "subject": {
          "reference": "urn:uuid:11111111-1111-4111-8111-111111111111"
        },
        "payload": [
          {
            "contentString": "{patientName} has a history of mild essential hypertension diagnosed 3 years ago and seasonal allergic rhinitis. She has no known chronic liver disease, no prior diagnosis of viral hepatitis, and no history of gallstones. She has never required intensive care or prolonged hospitalization. About 8 years ago she was hospitalized overnight for dehydration related to viral gastroenteritis and recovered fully.\n\nShe reports intermittent use of over-the-counter acetaminophen for tension headaches, generally within recommended doses, and occasional herbal supplements marketed for energy and weight management. She uses alcohol sparingly and denies binge drinking. She has no smoking history and denies recreational drug use. There is no known history of blood transfusions, but she has one tattoo obtained in a licensed studio in her 20s. She is in a monogamous relationship and reports no recent travel.\n\nOver the past month, {patientName} has experienced increasing fatigue, reduced appetite, intermittent nausea, dark urine, and a dull right upper quadrant ache. She denies hematemesis, melena, or severe abdominal distension. She has not previously undergone liver biopsy or hepatobiliary surgery. Her current symptoms and supplement exposure make medication- or supplement-related liver inflammation a relevant consideration while broader hepatic workup proceeds."
          }
        ]
      }
    }
  ]
}